        "bookTile": "Algorithms to Live By",
        "page": 273,
        "location": "4174-4177",
        "dateOfCreation": "Added on Saturday, October 2, 2021 9:18:29 PM",
        "content": "John Maynard Keynes, once said that “successful investing is anticipating the anticipations of others.” For a share of stock to be sold at, say, $60, the buyer must believe he can sell it later for $70—to someone who believes he can sell it for $80 to someone who believes he can sell it for $90 to someone who believes he can sell it for $100 to someone else. In this way, the value of a stock isn’t what people think it’s worth but what people think people think it’s worth.",
