        "content": "The philosopher Onora O’Neill once declared, “Well-placed trust grows out of active inquiry rather than blind acceptance.”2 That seems right. If we want to be able to trust the world around us, we need to show an interest and ask a few basic questions. I hope I’ve persuaded you that those questions aren’t obscure or overly technical; they are what any thoughtful, curious person would be happy to ask. And despite all the confusions of the modern world, it has never been easier to find answers to those questions. Curiosity, it turns out, can be a remarkably powerful thing.",
