        "content": "This method has the advantage that though the pupil may never atain the final stage, which is usually the case, he still may proft from instruction and will become more experienced and wiser—if not for the purposes of the school, then at least for those of life. But if this method is inverted, then the pupils are apt to catch something of cleverness before their reasoning faculties have been developed and to take away from school a borrowed knowledge, like something that is glued to them but has not been assimilated by them, and their spiritual faculties remain sterile as before, but at the same time much vitiated by a spurious learnedness. Terein is the cause why we frequently meet men of learning (or rather of instruction) who show so litle reason, and why so many more blockheads come into the world out of colleges than from any other social class",
