        "page": 32,
        "location": "484-494",
        "dateOfCreation": "Added on Monday, April 22, 2024 9:29:26 PM",
        "content": "Curiously, he seems to have missed the best lesson, taught by Grandmother Milhous, a Quaker who used “plain speech,” addressing her family as “thee” and “thou.” Nixon’s youngest brother, Edward, recalled how their grandmother told her grandchildren not to hate their enemies. “She said, ‘Let them sound off. Let it go in one ear and out the other and settle some place else. Listen and say nothing, that’s the best thing to do,” according to Edward. She compared anger and the desire for revenge to a spring flower that would die out. “Never say, ‘I hate,’ ” said Grandmother Milhous. “Don’t call anyone a liar. You’re not sure and if you are sure why advertise it? Let the lie die. Use silence.”57 Nixon was more heedful of a verse from a Longfellow poem she sent him: The heights of great men reached and kept Were not attained by sudden flight But they while their companions slept Were toiling upward in the night.58",
